    description: 'Infection of the endocardial surface of the heart, typically involving heart valves, caused by bacteria (most commonly) or fungi, with high morbidity and mortality.',
    pathophysiology: 'Bacteremia seeds damaged or prosthetic valve endocardium. Platelets and fibrin deposit on damaged endothelium forming sterile vegetations (NBTE). Bacteria colonize these vegetations, creating infected masses containing organisms, fibrin, platelets, and inflammatory cells. Vegetations cause valvular destruction/regurgitation, embolize to distant organs (brain, kidneys, spleen, lungs for right-sided), and trigger immune complex deposition. Common organisms: viridans streptococci (subacute native valve), S. aureus (acute, IVDU), enterococci, HACEK group.',
    clinicalFeatures: ['Fever (most common symptom)', 'New or changing cardiac murmur', 'Constitutional: malaise, weight loss, night sweats', 'Embolic phenomena: stroke, splenic/renal infarcts, septic pulmonary emboli (right-sided)', 'Janeway lesions (painless palmar/plantar macules)', 'Osler nodes (painful fingertip nodules)', 'Splinter hemorrhages', 'Roth spots (retinal hemorrhages with pale center)', 'Splenomegaly'],
    diagnostics: ['Modified Duke criteria (2 major, 1 major+3 minor, or 5 minor for definite)', 'Blood cultures: at least 3 sets from separate venipunctures before antibiotics', 'Echocardiography: TTE first, TEE if TTE negative but high clinical suspicion, prosthetic valves, or complications', 'Findings: vegetations, abscess, new valvular regurgitation, dehiscence of prosthetic valve', 'CBC, CRP/ESR, urinalysis (hematuria), rheumatoid factor'],
