    clinicalFeatures: ['Exertional dyspnea', 'Angina (supply-demand mismatch from hypertrophy)', 'Syncope or presyncope (especially exertional)', 'Palpitations', 'Harsh crescendo-decrescendo systolic murmur at LLSB/apex that increases with Valsalva and standing (decreased preload increases obstruction)', 'Bifid (spike-and-dome) arterial pulse', 'S4 gallop', 'Laterally displaced PMI', 'Some patients asymptomatic, diagnosed on screening'],
    diagnostics: ['Echocardiography: LVH >=15mm (or >=13mm with positive family history), SAM, LVOT gradient (resting and provoked with Valsalva)', 'Cardiac MRI: extent of hypertrophy, late gadolinium enhancement for fibrosis (prognostic)', 'ECG: LVH, deep T-wave inversions, pathologic Q waves, LA enlargement', 'Holter monitor for non-sustained VT (SCD risk factor)', 'Exercise stress test for symptoms, BP response, and provoked gradient', 'Genetic testing and cascade family screening', 'HCM Risk-SCD calculator for ICD decision-making'],
    treatment: ['Avoid dehydration, excessive alcohol, and high-intensity competitive athletics', 'Obstructive HCM: beta-blockers (first-line), disopyramide (add to beta-blocker), verapamil (if beta-blocker intolerant)', 'Mavacamten (cardiac myosin inhibitor) for symptomatic obstructive HCM', 'Septal reduction therapy if refractory: surgical myectomy (gold standard) or alcohol septal ablation', 'ICD for high SCD risk (5-year risk >=6% by HCM Risk-SCD, or additional risk factors)', 'Non-obstructive HCM: treat symptoms, standard HF therapy if EF declines', 'AFib: anticoagulate all HCM patients with AFib regardless of CHA2DS2-VASc', 'Heart transplant for end-stage (burnt-out) HCM'],
    complications: ['Sudden cardiac death (especially in young athletes)', 'Heart failure (diastolic or systolic in burnt-out phase)', 'Atrial fibrillation with high stroke risk', 'Infective endocarditis (obstructive HCM)', 'Progressive symptoms limiting quality of life'],
    patientExplanation: 'Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is a genetic condition where the heart muscle becomes abnormally thick, which can block blood from leaving the heart and make it stiff. It is the most common cause of sudden cardiac death in young athletes. Many people with HCM have no symptoms and live normal lives, but some develop shortness of breath, chest pain, or fainting. Treatment includes medicines to relax the heart, avoiding intense competitive sports, and sometimes a procedure to thin the muscle or an implanted defibrillator for protection.',
    emergencySigns: ['Syncope (especially exertional) in known or suspected HCM', 'Cardiac arrest', 'Acute heart failure', 'Sustained VT', 'Severe dynamic LVOT obstruction with hypotension'],
