    patientExplanation: 'Restrictive cardiomyopathy means the heart muscle has become stiff and cannot relax properly to fill with blood. The heart may pump normally, but it cannot expand enough between beats. This is often caused by substances building up in the heart muscle, such as abnormal proteins (amyloidosis) or iron. Treatment depends on the underlying cause. Fluid pills help with swelling, and newer medications can treat specific causes like amyloidosis.',
    emergencySigns: ['Acute decompensated heart failure', 'New high-degree AV block', 'Syncope', 'Rapid AFib with hemodynamic compromise', 'Refractory volume overload'],
