    description: 'Life-threatening compression of the heart by fluid accumulating in the pericardial space, impairing diastolic filling and causing hemodynamic collapse.',
    pathophysiology: 'Pericardial fluid accumulation raises intrapericardial pressure above cardiac chamber diastolic pressures, compressing the heart and impairing filling. Rate of accumulation matters more than volume: rapid (trauma, aortic dissection, ventricular rupture) 100-200ml can be fatal; slow (malignancy, uremia) may tolerate >1L. Right-sided chambers compressed first (lowest pressures). Equalization of diastolic pressures occurs. Compensatory tachycardia and vasoconstriction maintain CO initially, then decompensation.',
    clinicalFeatures: ['Beck triad: hypotension, distended neck veins, muffled heart sounds', 'Tachycardia', 'Pulsus paradoxus (>10mmHg SBP drop with inspiration)', 'Dyspnea', 'Tachypnea', 'Cool, clammy extremities', 'Ewart sign (dullness and bronchial breathing below left scapula from compressed lung)', 'Narrow pulse pressure', 'Altered mental status in severe cases'],
