    pathophysiology: 'Plaque rupture/erosion with non-occlusive thrombus or transient occlusion with spontaneous lysis reduces but does not completely eliminate coronary blood flow. Subendocardial (non-transmural) ischemia and necrosis occur. Unlike STEMI, some residual flow exists. Biomarker elevation (troponin) distinguishes NSTEMI from unstable angina. Risk stratification (TIMI, GRACE scores) guides timing of invasive strategy.',
    clinicalFeatures: ['Chest pain/pressure similar to STEMI but may be less severe', 'Pain at rest or with minimal exertion', 'Crescendo angina pattern', 'Associated symptoms: dyspnea, diaphoresis, nausea', 'May present with new heart failure or arrhythmia', 'ECG: ST depression, T-wave inversions, or non-specific changes (no persistent ST elevation)'],
    diagnostics: ['Serial high-sensitivity troponin (at presentation and 3-6 hours)', 'ECG: ST depression, T-wave inversions, or may be normal (no ST elevation)', 'TIMI or GRACE risk score for risk stratification', 'Echocardiography: wall motion abnormalities', 'Coronary angiography: early invasive (<24h) for high-risk, urgent (<2h) for refractory symptoms or hemodynamic instability', 'BNP for prognostication'],
    treatment: ['Dual antiplatelet therapy: aspirin + P2Y12 inhibitor (ticagrelor preferred)', 'Anticoagulation: enoxaparin, UFH, fondaparinux, or bivalirudin', 'Early invasive strategy (angiography within 24h) for high-risk patients', 'Conservative strategy with stress testing for low-risk patients', 'Beta-blocker, statin, ACEi/ARB', 'Nitroglycerin for ongoing ischemia', 'GP IIb/IIIa inhibitors in select high-risk patients during PCI', 'Risk factor modification and cardiac rehabilitation'],
    complications: ['Progression to STEMI', 'Recurrent ischemia', 'Heart failure', 'Arrhythmias', 'Cardiogenic shock (less common than STEMI)', 'Death (in-hospital mortality ~3-5%)'],
    patientExplanation: 'An NSTEMI heart attack means part of your heart muscle is being damaged because a coronary artery is partially blocked. Unlike a STEMI, the blockage is not complete, so the damage may be less severe, but it is still a serious medical emergency. You will receive blood thinners and other medications right away. Most patients undergo cardiac catheterization within 24 hours to find and treat the blockage. Recovery includes medications, lifestyle changes, and cardiac rehabilitation.',
    emergencySigns: ['Ongoing chest pain despite treatment', 'Hemodynamic instability', 'Rising troponin with worsening symptoms', 'New arrhythmia or heart failure', 'Cardiogenic shock'],
