    clinicalFeatures: ['Substernal chest pressure/tightness/heaviness during exertion', 'Predictable onset at consistent level of exertion', 'Lasts 3-5 minutes, relieved by rest or sublingual nitroglycerin within 3-5 minutes', 'May radiate to arm, jaw, neck, back', 'Associated dyspnea', 'Canadian Cardiovascular Society grading (I-IV)', 'Anginal equivalents: exertional dyspnea, fatigue (especially women, elderly, diabetics)'],
    diagnostics: ['Exercise stress ECG: ST depression >=1mm at 80ms after J point', 'Stress imaging (nuclear MPI, stress echo, stress CMR) for higher sensitivity/specificity', 'Coronary CTA for anatomic assessment', 'Coronary angiography if high-risk stress test or symptoms despite medical therapy', 'Baseline ECG, lipid panel, HbA1c, BMP', 'Calcium score for asymptomatic risk assessment'],
    treatment: ['Sublingual nitroglycerin for acute symptom relief', 'First-line antianginals: beta-blockers or CCBs (amlodipine, diltiazem)', 'Second-line: long-acting nitrates (isosorbide mononitrate - need nitrate-free interval), ranolazine', 'Aspirin 81mg daily', 'High-intensity statin', 'Blood pressure control, glycemic management', 'Lifestyle: smoking cessation, exercise, Mediterranean diet', 'Revascularization (PCI or CABG) if refractory to medical therapy or high-risk anatomy'],
    complications: ['Acute coronary syndrome (plaque rupture)', 'Heart failure from chronic ischemia', 'Arrhythmias', 'Limitation of daily activities and quality of life'],
    patientExplanation: 'Stable angina is a type of chest pain or pressure that happens when you exert yourself, like walking uphill or climbing stairs, because narrowed arteries cannot supply enough blood to your heart during exercise. It goes away with rest or a nitroglycerin tablet under your tongue. It is your heart warning sign that blood flow is limited. Medications can control symptoms and reduce risk, but you should call 911 if the pain pattern changes, occurs at rest, or does not go away with nitroglycerin.',
    emergencySigns: ['Change in anginal pattern (more frequent, less exertion, at rest) suggesting ACS', 'Angina not relieved by nitroglycerin within 5 minutes', 'Associated syncope or severe dyspnea', 'Angina with hemodynamic changes'],
