    clinicalFeatures: ['Sudden onset severe "tearing" or "ripping" chest/back pain', 'Anterior chest pain (ascending), interscapular pain (descending)', 'Hypertension (most common) or hypotension (rupture, tamponade)', 'Blood pressure differential between arms >20mmHg', 'Pulse deficit (asymmetric pulses)', 'Aortic regurgitation murmur (Type A)', 'Neurological deficits (stroke from carotid involvement)', 'Malperfusion syndromes: limb ischemia, renal failure, mesenteric ischemia, spinal cord ischemia (paraplegia)'],
    diagnostics: ['CT angiography of chest/abdomen/pelvis (first-line, rapid and highly accurate)', 'Intimal flap separating true and false lumen', 'TEE (if too unstable for CT, excellent for ascending aorta)', 'MRA (most accurate but time-consuming, not for unstable patients)', 'CXR: widened mediastinum, abnormal aortic contour (may be normal)', 'D-dimer negative has high negative predictive value', 'Aortic dissection detection risk score (ADD-RS) guides imaging'],
    treatment: ['Type A: emergent surgical repair (mortality increases 1-2% per hour without surgery)', 'Type B uncomplicated: medical management with IV anti-impulse therapy', 'Blood pressure target: SBP 100-120 mmHg', 'Heart rate target: <60 bpm', 'IV beta-blockers first (esmolol, labetalol) THEN vasodilators (nitroprusside) - order matters to avoid reflex tachycardia', 'Pain control (morphine)', 'Type B complicated (malperfusion, rupture, rapid expansion): TEVAR (thoracic endovascular aortic repair)', 'Long-term: beta-blocker, serial imaging surveillance, blood pressure control'],
