    clinicalFeatures: ['Acute dyspnea (most common symptom)', 'Pleuritic chest pain', 'Tachycardia', 'Tachypnea', 'Hemoptysis', 'Syncope (suggests massive PE)', 'Hypotension (massive PE)', 'Leg swelling/pain (concurrent DVT)', 'Distended neck veins, RV heave', 'Low-grade fever', 'May be asymptomatic'],
    diagnostics: ['CT pulmonary angiography (first-line diagnostic imaging)', 'D-dimer (high sensitivity, low specificity - use to rule out in low probability)', 'Wells score or Geneva score for pretest probability', 'V/Q scan if CT contraindicated (renal failure, contrast allergy)', 'Echocardiography: RV dilation, McConnell sign (RV free wall akinesis with preserved apex), for risk stratification', 'Troponin and BNP for risk stratification', 'Lower extremity ultrasound for DVT', 'ABG: hypoxemia, hypocapnia, respiratory alkalosis, elevated A-a gradient'],
    treatment: ['Anticoagulation (therapeutic dose immediately if high suspicion, even before imaging confirmed)', 'Low-risk PE: DOACs (rivaroxaban or apixaban as single-drug approach)', 'Intermediate-risk PE: UFH, close monitoring, consider escalation if deterioration', 'Massive PE with hemodynamic instability: systemic thrombolysis (alteplase 100mg over 2h)', 'Surgical embolectomy or catheter-directed therapy if thrombolysis fails or contraindicated', 'IVC filter if anticoagulation absolutely contraindicated', 'Duration: 3 months minimum, indefinite if unprovoked with low bleeding risk', 'Early ambulation'],
    complications: ['Death (massive PE mortality 25-65%)', 'RV failure', 'Chronic thromboembolic pulmonary hypertension (CTEPH) in 2-4%', 'Recurrent VTE', 'Post-PE syndrome (persistent dyspnea, exercise intolerance)', 'Bleeding from anticoagulation'],
    patientExplanation: 'A pulmonary embolism is a blood clot that has traveled from a vein (usually in the leg) to the lungs, blocking blood flow. It causes sudden shortness of breath and chest pain. A large clot can be life-threatening. Treatment involves blood thinners to prevent more clots and, in severe cases, clot-dissolving medication. You will need to take blood thinners for at least 3 months. Recognizing the symptoms early and getting treatment quickly is critical.',
    emergencySigns: ['Massive PE with hypotension or shock', 'Syncope', 'Severe hypoxemia not improving with oxygen', 'Cardiac arrest (PEA)', 'RV failure signs (distended neck veins, hypotension, tachycardia)'],
