    patientExplanation: 'A deep vein thrombosis (DVT) is a blood clot in a deep vein, usually in the leg. It causes swelling, pain, and redness in the affected leg. The biggest danger is that the clot can break loose and travel to the lungs, causing a pulmonary embolism, which can be life-threatening. Treatment involves blood thinners for at least 3 months to dissolve the clot and prevent new ones. Moving around (not bed rest) is encouraged during treatment.',
    emergencySigns: ['Symptoms of PE (sudden dyspnea, chest pain, syncope)', 'Phlegmasia (massively swollen, blue, painful limb)', 'Bilateral lower extremity DVT (consider IVC thrombus or pelvic mass)', 'Upper extremity DVT with SVC syndrome symptoms'],
